{
  "text": "Similarly, despite the literature identifying the need for sufficient time to debrief, there is no research evidence suggesting an ideal amount of time or percentage allocation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . For example, [CITATION_3] found no evidence to support a popular guidance model used in nursing, which advises that \"debriefing sessions should be approximately two to three times the length of the scenario itself\" as such periods allow sufficient time for students to reflect on and think deeply about their performance (Waxman, 2010, p. 34) . In particular, [CITATION_4] found nonsignificant effects in short (shorter than 15 min) or long (longer than 15 min) debriefing when expert modeling was incorporated. As debriefing is typically much longer in aviation than in the studies examined by [CITATION_5] , further research is needed to determine how long debriefing should last for in training pilots.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "20761439",
    "[CITATION_2]": "145652022",
